#Text=West Bali National Park
#Text=West Bali National
#Text=Park
#Text=is the only national park on the island of Bali in Indonesia .
#Text=Understand
#Text=West Bali National Park ( Taman Nasional Bali Barat in Bahasa Indonesia ) is the most north-westerly point of Bali .
#Text=It includes the whole of the Prapat Agung Peninsula , and large swathes of land around the towns of Gilimanuk , Cekik and Banyuwedang .
#Text=The official area inside the park boundaries is 190 km ² , with a further 580 km ² of protected reserve in the highlands to the east .
#Text=In total this accounts for some ten percent of Bali 's total land area .
#Text=History
#Text=The park was first recognised as an area of importance in 1917 when the council of Bali rulers designated it as a nature park .
#Text=It was established as an Indonesian National Park in 1941 .
#Text=Landscape
#Text=The habitat is very varied with rainforest , dry savanna , acacia scrub and lowland forests , as well as more montane forests in the higher centre .
#Text=There are also some pockets of dense mangrove forest .
#Text=In the north of the park there is an obvious north jutting peninsula called Prapat Agung .
#Text=Around this peninsula there are long stretches of protected beach and offshore coral reef as well , as a small offshore island called Menjangan .
#Text=The latter is a very popular diving destination .
#Text=There are several long extinct volcanoes in the protected reserve area to the east , with Mount Patas ( 1,412 metres ) and Mount Merbuk ( 1,388 metres ) being the highest points .
#Text=These peaks are dominant visual landscape features from within every area of the park .
#Text=Flora and fauna

#Text=160 species of bird have been recorded in the park , including the near extinct Bali Starling , Bali 's only endemic vertebrate species , and a key reason why this national park was created in the first place .
#Text=By 2001 , as few as six individuals were thought to survive in the wild , all of them in this park .
#Text=Since then captive breeding and re-introduction efforts have continued apace , but poaching pressures are a large problem .
#Text=With that in mind , a second re-introduction programme was started in remote regions of Nusa Penida in 2004 .
#Text=Keen birdwatchers can find a checklist of likely species and their status here .
#Text=Mammals found inside the park include Banteng , a species of wild cattle from which the familiar Bali cows are descended .
#Text=Java Rusa and Indian Muntjac deer are quite widespread , and Menjangan Island is in fact named after these ( Menjangan means deer in Bahasa Indonesia ) .
#Text=Wild Boar and Leopard Cats are both quite common but seldom encountered .

#Text=A Bali Tiger ( a full sub-species of Tiger ) was shot here in 1937 , and despite rumours to the contrary , that is the last ever confirmed sighting of an animal considered extinct since that moment .
#Text=Climate
#Text=Not noticeably different from the rest of Bali or eastern Java , but it may feel a little hotter and drier in the dry season here than in southern parts of Bali .
#Text=Bali is always warm , humid and tropical , remaining around 30-35°C ( 85-95°F ) all year round .
#Text=The April –

#Text=October dry season and November – March rainy seasons are only relative , with plenty of rainfall around the year , but the Balinese winter is cloudier , more humid and with a higher chance of thunderstorms .
#Text=Bali Barat National Park Office HQ
#Text=, Jl Raya Cekik-Gilimanuk , Jembrana , Bali 82253 , ☏ +6236561060 , fax : +6236561479 , ✉ tnbb@telkom.net . 7:30AM-5PM .
#Text=Bali Barat National Park Vistor 's Centre
#Text=, Labuhan Lalang , ✉ tnbb@telkom.net . 7:30AM-5PM .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Most visitors to the park arrive along the north coast road from Lovina ( about 90 minutes ) or Pemuteran ( about 15 minutes ) .
#Text=Others come from the south via Gilimanuk ( about 15 minutes )
#Text=All visitors should check in at one of the two park offices ( PHPA ) for information , and to purchase permits and arrange guides .
#Text=The headquarters is at the village of Cekik just south of the Gilimanuk in the west .
#Text=The other is at Labuan Lalang on the north coast from where boats to Menjangan Island depart .
#Text=The main ranger station is on the road between the two offices at Sumber Klampok .
#Text=The park staff are welcoming , helpful and will arrange guided tours for you .
#Text=Fees and permits
#Text=Permits and obligatory guides are available at the park headquarters at Cekik and the office at Labuhan Lalang .
#Text=The official permit charge is Rp 25,000 per person .
#Text=The cost of a guide is negotiable .
#Text=Use your common sense and do not be tight .
#Text=A sensible range would be about Rp 50,000 to 100,000 for a half to full day .
#Text=Get around
#Text=Only a small portion of the park is open to visitors , and this rule must be respected .
#Text=There are two key ways to explore the park : either hiking the trails or concentrating on marine aspects .
#Text=Walking the trails must be done with an official guide from one of the national park offices ( most normally the one at Cekik ) .
#Text=Boat trips to Menjangan and around Gilimanuk Bay can be organised in advance ( ask at your hotel ) , or by charter on the day you arrive .
#Text=See and do
#Text=The official park trails should be explored with a guide recommended by the national park office .
#Text=This is actually a rule but it is sometimes ' quietly ' ignored .
#Text=Please do not do this nor encourage the practice , despite the very irresponsible advice given in some printed travel guides to do so .
#Text=The Tegal Blunder Trail is most popular with birdwatchers , and it is an easy two-hour walk .
#Text=The ranger checkpoint is at the village of Slumber Klampok about 20 minutes west of Cekik .
#Text=From the same checkpoint you can take the more strenuous Gunung Klatakan Trail to the south east .
#Text=This is tougher walking for about five hours , but it takes you through some memorable rainforest .
#Text=There are other trails and opportunities for interesting hikes , but these are the two most popular and the easiest .
#Text=Ask guides about other opportunities at the time , particularly those involving hiking deeper into the Prapat Agung Peninsula .
#Text=The uninhabited Menjangan Island is a must-do for any visitor to Bali interested in marine life , snorkelling or diving .
#Text=Boats leave from the beach at Labuan Lalang at the northern edge of Teluk Terima bay , and can chartered on the day .
#Text=Groups of tourists often club together at Labuan Lalang in the mornings for that very purpose .
#Text=Any boat charter must be accompanied by a guide , and you must purchase a permit ( Rp 25,000 per person ) from the national park office in the main Labuhan Lalang car park .
#Text=Many of Bali 's dive operators based in the southern tourist regions offer dive excursions specifically to Menjangan .
#Text=The snorkelling here is probably the best on Bali with good clear water and calm seas .
#Text=There is a notable temple on Menjangan called Puri Gili Kencana which is certainly worth a visit .
#Text=You can walk around the whole of Menjangan in about 1 hour and 15 minutes .
#Text=If you take it slower though there is plenty of natural coastal beauty to absorb .
#Text=Gilimanuk Bay
#Text=snakes into the south western tip of the Prapat Agung peninsula , and the park office can arrange a guided boat trip for you in a traditional outrigger .
#Text=Expect to pay about Rp 300,000 per hour including guide fees .
#Text=The bay is quiet and supports a rich diverstity of marine life .
#Text=There are some notable areas of mangrove forest fringing the bay , and these act as a natural nursery for the diverse fish life in the area .
